        "author_role": "REVIEWER",
        "timestamp": "2020-10-14 15:46:57.000000000",
        "message": "Patch Set 1:\n\nI am not sure what the previous trigger specifies. Can we add merge job as the trigger, so that the CSIT will run everytime when a new code is merged into the repo.\n\nI will change the image versions to \"latest\", so that when it runs, it will pick up the latest built image.",
        "patchset_number": 1
      },
      {
        "id": "f533182201f8ec02a1a41007babe44af89aff5b1",
        "author": {
          "account_id": 3949,
          "name": "Lasse Kaihlavirta",
          "display_name": null,
          "email": "l.kaihlavirt@partner.samsung.com",
          "username": "kaihlavi"
        },
        "author_role": "OWNER",
        "timestamp": "2020-10-14 16:00:46.000000000",
        "message": "Patch Set 1:\n\n> Patch Set 1:\n> \n> I am not sure what the previous trigger specifies. Can we add merge job as the trigger, so that the CSIT will run everytime when a new code is merged into the repo.\n> \n> I will change the image versions to \"latest\", so that when it runs, it will pick up the latest built image.\n\nI would advise against using \"latest' tag for tested images in CSITs in general and particularly in the OPTF CSITs at the moment - have you noticed that also your frankfurt jobs currently produce the same images with \"latest'?  \n\nNote that we are planning to improve the CSIT structure (especially the docker image-CSIT-relations) in Honolulu (see https://wiki.onap.org/display/DW/Moving+CSIT+to+project+repositories) and the triggering mechanism should see some changes as part of that exercise anyway. \n\nThe CSITs are scheduled to run daily anyway, so can you to wait with the job trigger until we have the above plan figured out?",
        "patchset_number": 1
      },
